					<div id="mw-content-text" class="mw-body-content"><div class="mw-subjectpageheader">
</div><div class="mw-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang="en" dir="ltr"><div class="shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style="display:none">Portion of a disk enclosed by two radii and an arc</div>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1320445320">.mw-parser-output .hatnote{font-style:italic}.mw-parser-output div.hatnote{padding-left:1.6em;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .hatnote i{font-style:normal}.mw-parser-output .hatnote+link+.hatnote{margin-top:-0.5em}@media print{body.ns-0 .mw-parser-output .hatnote{display:none!important}}</style><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Not to be confused with <a href="/wiki/Circular_section" title="Circular section">circular section</a>.</div>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Circle_arc.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/da/Circle_arc.svg/250px-Circle_arc.svg.png" decoding="async" width="250" height="226" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/da/Circle_arc.svg/500px-Circle_arc.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="779" data-file-height="703" /></a><figcaption>The minor sector is shaded in green while the major sector is shaded white.</figcaption></figure>
<p>A <b>circular sector</b>, also known as <b>circle sector</b> or <b>disk sector</b> or simply a <b>sector</b> (symbol: <b>⌔</b>), is the portion of a <a href="/wiki/Disk_(mathematics)" title="Disk (mathematics)">disk</a> (a <a href="/wiki/Closed_region" class="mw-redirect" title="Closed region">closed region</a> bounded by a circle) enclosed by two <a href="/wiki/Radius" title="Radius">radii</a> and an <a href="/wiki/Circular_arc" title="Circular arc">arc</a>, with the smaller <a href="/wiki/Area_(geometry)" class="mw-redirect" title="Area (geometry)">area</a> being known as the <i>minor sector</i> and the larger being the <i>major sector</i>.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>1<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> In the diagram, <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">θ</span> is the <a href="/wiki/Central_angle" title="Central angle">central angle</a>, <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">r</span> the radius of the circle, and <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">L</span> is the arc length of the minor sector.
</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc" />
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Types">Types</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Circular_sector&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Types"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A sector with the central angle of 180° is called a <i><a href="/wiki/Disk_(geometry)" class="mw-redirect" title="Disk (geometry)">half-disk</a></i> and is bounded by a <a href="/wiki/Diameter" title="Diameter">diameter</a> and a <a href="/wiki/Semicircle" title="Semicircle">semicircle</a>. <span class="anchor" id="Quadrant"></span><span class="anchor" id="Sextant"></span><span class="anchor" id="Octant"></span>Sectors with other central angles are sometimes given special names, such as <b>quadrants</b> (90°), <b>sextants</b> (60°), and <b>octants</b> (45°), which come from the sector being one quarter, sixth or eighth part of a full circle, respectively.
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Area">Area</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Circular_sector&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Area"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1320445320" /><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="/wiki/Circular_arc#Sector_area" title="Circular arc">Circular arc §&#160;Sector area</a></div>
<p>The total area of a circle is <span class="texhtml"><i>πr</i><span style="padding-left:0.12em;"><sup>2</sup></span></span>. The area of the sector can be obtained by multiplying the circle's area by the ratio of the angle <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">θ</span> (expressed in radians) and <span class="texhtml">2<i>π</i></span> (because the area of the sector is directly proportional to its angle, and <span class="texhtml">2<i>π</i></span> is the angle for the whole circle, in radians):
<span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle A=\pi r^{2}\,{\frac {\theta }{2\pi }}={\frac {r^{2}\theta }{2}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mi>A</mi>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mi>&#x03C0;<!-- π --></mi>
        <msup>
          <mi>r</mi>
          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mspace width="thinmathspace" />
